# YAML 1.2
# Citation File Format — https://citation-file-format.github.io/
cff-version: 1.2.0
title: >-
  sae-deception-multiagent-rag: Probing for Deception in Multi-Agent
  RAG Pipelines Using Sparse Autoencoders
message: >-
  If you use this software or the ideas in it, please cite it using
  the metadata below.
type: software
authors:
  - given-names: Vidura
    email: businessaividura@viduraaitech.space
repository-code: 'https://github.com/Vidura-Wijekoon/sae-deception-multiagent-rag'
abstract: >-
  An open-source research preview applying sparse autoencoder probes,
  linear probes, and attribution-graph tracing to a LangGraph
  retrieval-augmented generation pipeline. Targets cross-agent
  activation transfer, retrieval-time amplification of adversarial
  features, and cross-model generalisation of deception probes.
  Anchored on Sharkey et al. (2025), "Open Problems in Mechanistic
  Interpretability."
keywords:
  - mechanistic-interpretability
  - sparse-autoencoders
  - ai-safety
  - multi-agent
  - retrieval-augmented-generation
  - deception-detection
  - prompt-injection
  - langgraph
  - gemma-scope
license: MIT
version: 0.0.1
date-released: '2026-05-28'
references:
  - type: article
    title: Open Problems in Mechanistic Interpretability
    authors:
      - family-names: Sharkey
        given-names: Lee
    year: 2025
    url: 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.16496'
  - type: article
    title: >-
      Gemma Scope: Open Sparse Autoencoders Everywhere All At Once on
      Gemma 2
    authors:
      - family-names: Lieberum
        given-names: Tom
    year: 2024
    url: 'https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.05147'
